photo.title: Henry Calthrop Hollway-Calthrop; Austin Lamont (1905-1969)
photo.description: Bookplate: H. C. Hollway-Calthrop dated: Florence Dec. 1883 Inscription: A. Lamont Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call number: LatC L7649 518d

photo.title: H. Pfau, Winterthur (Switzerland); David Sulzer, 1706
photo.description: Inscription at head: H: Pfau Winterthur [The Pfau (="peacock") family of Wintherthur, Switzerland, were notable 17th- and early 18th-century potters, oven-makers and -painters. Five of its members active in their craft were named Hans Heinrich: Hans Heinrich I (1559-1636), Hans Heinrich II (1598-1673), Hans Heinrich III (1642-1719), Hans Heinrich IV (1672-1714), and Hans Heinrich V (fl. 1702-1740?). Cf. their entries in Schweizerisches Künsterlexikon (Frauenfeld: Huber & Co., 1905-1917), 2. Bd., p. 539f; cf. also the entry for the Pfau family in the online SIKART Lexikon und Datenbank zur Kunst in der Schweiz und im Fürstentum Liechtenstein.] Inscription at foot: nunc Davidis Sulzeri. 1706. ["Der beste Winterthurer Ofenmaler des 18. Jahrhunderts war David Sulzer (1716-1792). Er weist in reiner Blumenmalerei, in stilisiertem Blumenornament, in kleinen Landschaften auf Wege, die den ausschliesslichen Ofenschmuck seit der Mitte des 18. Jahrhunderts ausmachen sollten." -- M. Lüthi, Bürgerliche Innendekoration des Spätbarock und Rokoko in der deutschen Schweiz (Zürich: Art. Institut Orell Füssli, 1927), p. 43 (citing an article by a Dr. Hafner in Winterthurer Neujahrsblatt 1876). Sulzer is also mentioned in A. Jacquemart, History of the Ceramic Art, tr. B. Palliser (London: Sampson Low et al., 1873), p. 490, and an example of his work in collaboration with potter Ottmar Vogler of Elgg is briefly described in B. Bucher, ed., Geschichte der Technischen Künste, 3. Bd. (Stuttgart: Union Deutsche Verlagsgesellschaft, 1893), p. 478.] Getty records a David Sulzer 1685-1762 , a Swiss stove painter Penn Libraries call number: GC5 C4534 542d All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: Ownership inscriptions of Joannes Kaufmannus, Daniel Graf, and Heinricus Pavanius (Winterthur, Switzerland)
photo.description: First inscription: Sum ex libris Ioan: Kaufmannj Vitodurani emptis ab haeredibus Matthiae Cellarij. Ano. 1539. [...]: 1439. M. Cellarius. [Ownership inscription of Joannes Kaufmannus of Winterthur, noting that this volume was purchased from the heirs of Matthias Cellarius (d. 1586; enrolled Universität Basel 1575/1576; pastor of Seuzach, Switzerland, near Winterthur, 1580-1586). The "Ano. 1539" is probably an attempt to supply a date to the imprint; at the end of the preface, the date "MDXLI" (1541) has been crossed out and replaced in ms. with "1539". A later hand appears to have interpreted it as "1439" and added a transcription of Cellarius's name.] Second inscription: Sum ex libris Danielis Comitis Vitoduranj Anno 1634. Nunc vero Heinrici Pavanij ibidem. 1663 [Ownership inscription of Daniel Graf, followed by ownership inscription of Heinricus Pavanius, both of Winterthur, Switzerland. The Graf family, like the Pfau family, were heavily involved in the pottery industry at Winterthur. Cf. The Grove Encyclopedia of Decorative Arts, ed. G. Campbell (Oxford: Oxford UP, 2006), v. 2, p. 558.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 C4534 542d All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.title: "Zu Brandes 750"
photo.description: zu Brandes 750 Dupl [Georg Friedrich Brandes (1709-1791) was a German jurist, overseer(?) of the University of Göttingen, and collector of books and art. The bulk of his notable library, some 22000 volumes, was sold in 1790 to Peter Friedrich Ludwig, Duke of Oldenburg (1755-1829) and formed the basis of the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg (founded 1792 and still in existence). Brandes also collected engravings and Michel Huber published a 2-volume catalog of the collection under the title Catalogue raisonné du cabinet d'estampes de feu Monsieur Brandes, secrétaire intime de la Chancellerie royale d'Hannovre (Leipzig: Rost, 1792-1794). These engravings appear to have been sold at auction in 1796. Two separate sales were planned: the first at Easter (18 April), comprising the English, German and Italian items; the second at Michaelmas (3 October), comprising items from France and the Netherlands. Cf. "Verkauf des Brandes'schen Kupferstich-Kabinets" in Neue Bibliothek der schönen Wissenschaften und der freyen Künste 56 (1795): 189-190, as well as the two sale catalogues: Premiere partie ou Écoles angloise, allemande et italienne, avec une grande collection de portraits: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de Pâques 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1795) and Seconde partie ou Écoles des Pays-Bas et Francoise: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de S. Michel 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1796). For more information on Brandes's library, including reproductions of his bookplate, see the online exhibition at the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg here, as well as G. Crusius, Aufklärung und Bibliophilie: Der Hannoveraner Sammler Georg Friedrich Brandes und seine Bibliothek (Heidelberg: Winter, 2008). Crusius also deals briefly with the engravings collection. photo.description: Bibliotheque du P[eti]t semin[ai]re de Chalons Seminarium Cathalaunense This is a stamp from the (diocesan) Petit seminaire de Châlons, founded by Louis-Antoine de Noailles, 1651-1729, bishop of Châlons, later archbishop of Paris, then given the cap in 1700, who was frequently accused (usually by Jesuits) of being a Jansenist. His support for theological and doctrinal works condemned as Jansenist, and for individuals accused of Jansenism was never sufficiently countered by his seemingly lukewarm repudiation of the heresy. He is frequently confused with other members of the Noailles family. The Grand seminaire de Chalons, also under the patronage of Louis-Antoine de Noailles, later became a Lazarist school. Châlons-sur-Marne became Châlons-en-Champagne by decree of June 11, 1995 Penn Libraries call number: FC65 C6543 C755 All images from this book
